# Objective

The objective of this session was to create the first API route using Express Router and connect it to the Express application.

This introduces route organization, making the backend easier to maintain as it grows.

---

# Why We Need Routes

As the application grows, we will have many endpoints.

For example:

```text
GET /products
GET /products/:id
POST /products
PUT /products/:id
DELETE /products/:id
```

If every route were placed inside `app.js`, the file would become very large and difficult to maintain.

Instead, Express allows us to organize routes into separate files based on their purpose.

---

# Step 1 – Create `productRoutes.js`

Inside the `routes` folder, create a new file named:

```text
backend/
└── src/
    └── routes/
        └── productRoutes.js
```

The project structure now becomes:

```text
backend/
│
├── src/
│   ├── config/
│   ├── controllers/
│   ├── middleware/
│   ├── models/
│   ├── routes/
│   │   └── productRoutes.js
│   ├── services/
│   ├── utils/
│   └── app.js
│
├── package.json
├── package-lock.json
└── server.js
```

---

# Why Create a Separate Routes File?

Each feature in the application should have its own routes file.

Examples:

```text
routes/
├── productRoutes.js
├── authRoutes.js
├── orderRoutes.js
├── paymentRoutes.js
├── reviewRoutes.js
├── customerRoutes.js
```

This keeps the project organized and makes it easier to locate and manage routes related to a specific feature.

---

# What is an Express Router?

An Express Router is a mini version of an Express application.

Instead of placing every route inside `app.js`, each router is responsible for handling routes related to one feature.

For this project, `productRoutes.js` will handle all product-related requests.

---

# Beauty Shop Analogy

Imagine a customer enters the beauty shop.

Instead of one employee handling every task, there are different departments.

```text
Reception
     │
 ┌───┼────────┐
 │   │        │
 ▼   ▼        ▼
Products Orders Customers
```

Each department has its own receptionist.

In Express, each department is represented by a Router.

