# Step 2 – Create the Product Router

Open:

```text
backend/src/routes/productRoutes.js
```

Paste the following code:

```javascript
const express = require("express");

const router = express.Router();

// GET /products
router.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.json({
    message: "List of products will appear here."
  });
});

module.exports = router;
```

---

# Code Explanation

## Import Express

```javascript
const express = require("express");
```

Imports the Express framework into the file.

---

## Create a Router

```javascript
const router = express.Router();
```

Creates a new Express Router.

Unlike `app.js`, this is **not** the entire application.

It only manages product-related routes.

---

## Create the First Route

```javascript
router.get("/", (req, res) => {
```

Creates a GET endpoint.

Notice we use:

```javascript
router.get()
```

instead of

```javascript
app.get()
```

because this file represents a Router, not the entire application.

---

## Send a JSON Response

```javascript
res.json({
  message: "List of products will appear here."
});
```

Returns a JSON response to the client.

Expected response:

```json
{
  "message": "List of products will appear here."
}
```

JSON is the standard format used for communication between the backend and frontend.

---

## Export the Router

```javascript
module.exports = router;
```

Exports the Router so it can be imported into another file.

In our project, it will be imported into `app.js`.

