# Step 3 – Import the Router into `app.js`

Open:

```text
backend/src/app.js
```

At the top of the file, after importing Express, add:

```javascript
const productRoutes = require("./routes/productRoutes");
```

---

# Code Explanation

```javascript
const productRoutes = require("./routes/productRoutes");
```

This imports the Router from `productRoutes.js`.

Breaking it down:

* `./` → start in the current folder (`src`)
* `routes` → enter the `routes` folder
* `productRoutes` → load `productRoutes.js`

Node.js automatically finds the `.js` file, so the extension is omitted.

---

# Step 4 – Register the Router

After:

```javascript
app.use(express.json());
```

add:

```javascript
app.use("/products", productRoutes);
```

The updated `app.js` becomes:

```javascript
const express = require("express");
const productRoutes = require("./routes/productRoutes");

const app = express();

// Middleware
app.use(express.json());

// Product routes
app.use("/products", productRoutes);

// Home route
app.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Welcome to Queens' Touch Beauty Shop API! 🚀");
});

module.exports = app;
```

---

# What Does `app.use("/products", productRoutes)` Do?

This line tells Express:

> "Whenever a request starts with `/products`, send it to the `productRoutes` Router."

This connects the Router to the main application.

Without this line, Express would never use the routes defined in `productRoutes.js`.

---

# How Express Builds the Final Route

Inside `productRoutes.js`, we wrote:

```javascript
router.get("/");
```

Inside `app.js`, we registered:

```javascript
app.use("/products", productRoutes);
```

Express combines both parts.

```text
app.use("/products", ...)
+
router.get("/")
=
GET /products
```

This is why visiting:

```text
http://localhost:3000/products
```

executes the route inside `productRoutes.js`.

